React Arrow functions for components & Event Handlers 
cost Greeting = ({name}:{name: string}) => <h1> Hello {name}</h1>;
<button onClick={() => alert("clicked")}>Click Me</button> 
Different Scenarios for Arrow Functions
Shorthand for simple functions ‚Üí (a, b) => a + b
Callbacks (map, filter, reduce, forEach, etc.) ‚Üí arr.map(x => x * 2)
Event handlers in React ‚Üí <button onClick={() => ...}>
Functional React components ‚Üí const App = () => <div>Hello</div>
Avoiding this issues in objects/classes ‚Üí arrow keeps lexical this
function Person() {
  this.age = 0;

  setInterval(() => {
    this.age++; // 'this' refers to Person, not setInterval
    console.log(this.age);
  }, 1000);
}

new Person();
If we had used a normal function inside setInterval, this would not work as expected.

1.Props (short for ‚Äúproperties‚Äù) are how you pass data from a parent component to a child component.
2.Parent - Child Communication 
  Props let parents send data to children. 
function App() {
  return <Greeting name="Sivaraj" />;
}
3.Stateless ‚Üí Controlled by Parent
Props make components stateless and predictable.
Example: Parent controls what child displays.

Props vs State 
const Counter = ({ start }: { start: number }) => {
  const [count, setCount] = React.useState(start);
  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
};
start (prop) = given by parent
count (state) = managed inside Counter

We use props to make components reusable, dynamic, and customizable ‚Äî they are the "inputs" that flow down from parent to child in React.




